long_desc.thetext:
From 3.1 on the "this" qualifier is suggested by code assistance when completing on field names that have the same name as constructor or method parameters.

Unfortunately the field variable name is not succesfully applied when using the completion.

In contrast to previous releases the qualifier appears in the completion list:
  key    String 
  this.key    String - Test


sample:

public class Test {
	private String key;
	public Test(String key) {
		k           // try completion here
	}

	public void setKey(String key) {
		k           // try completion here
	}
}

The javadoc says that "Deleting text which completely contains the position deletes the position.", it does, however, not define what "completely contains" means. From the implementation of notDeleted() it appears that "completely contains" means a deletion that starts _before_ (not on or before) the start offset of the position, and extends to _after_ (not on or after) the end offset of the position. 

In your example, this is not the case: the position is merely shrinked to a zero-length position, but not removed. Due to updating behavior of DefaultPositionUpdater, such a zero-length position can never gain any length any more, and will remain zero-length until it is deleted by a change that encompasses it.

While this behavior makes sense in some situations, in does not in others; various other IPositionUpdater implementations exist in places where a different updating scheme is needed. We will probably not change the behavior of the default updater for compatibility reasons.

@see InclusivePositionUpdater
@see ExclusivePositionUpdater

