In linux advanced graphics mode, if I perform a transformation on gc first and then the reverse transformation, the clipping area for current gc get damaged. I  suspect this is due to kind of computing-precison lost.

Actually, I just want to restore the inital state before transformation, in Windows, I can use gc.setTransform(null) to achieve this, but in linux, seems this does nothing. So I have to perform the reverse transformation myself.

Meanwhile, the workaround is recording the clipping area manually before tranformation and set it back after, but I think it's better this is fixed in SWT.

Here is the test code:
----------------------------8<-----------------------------
gc.setAdvanced(true);

Region clip = new Region(Display.getDefault());
clip.add(0, 0, 450, 250);
gc.setClipping(clip);
clip.dispose();

Transform tr = new Transform(Display.getDefault());
tr.translate(154, 7);

Transform rtr = new Transform(Display.getDefault());
tr.translate(-154, -7);

Region rg = new Region(Display.getDefault());
gc.getClipping(rg);
System.out.println("initial clipping :" + rg.getBounds());

// perform transformation
gc.setTransform(tr);
// perform reverse transformation
gc.setTransform(rtr);
// this does nothing in linux
gc.setTransform(null);

gc.getClipping(rg);
System.out.println("initial clipping :" + rg.getBounds());

rg.dispose();
tr.dispose();
rtr.dispose();

I believe both problems have been fixed in the 3.3 stream. Please try the latest integration build and reopen if you still see a problem.

